702644f-a.text:
112 East 21st Street, adjointng the S. W. corner of Caton Avenue, showing the Clarkson Mansion, built in 1836. It was later known as the Midwood Club and was for a time used by the Brooklyn Union League after they gave up their Grant Square quarters. In the late 1930s it was known as the Sperry Memorial Butlding and was then the Flatbush branch of the Y. M. C. A. For additional
data see "The New York Times," Octoer 6, 1940.

702645f-a.text:
112 East 21st Street, adjoining the S. W. corner of Caton Ave., showing the Clarkson Mansion, built in 1836. Early in its history the house was purchased by a group of prominent Flatbush men who formed the Midwood Club and so named the mansion. Later the Midwood Club was purchased b leaders of tho Brooklyn Union League Club who made it their headquarters for a time. From 1927 to 1940 the house was the headquarters of the Flatbush branch of the Y. M. C. A. and was known as the Sperry Memorial Building. On January 21, 1940, A fire wrecked the structure and toward the end of the year, or early 1941, was torn down to make way for an apartment house. For additional data see 'The New York Times," October 6, 1940.
